WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.633 --> 00:00:02.567
[music playing]

00:00:08.233 --> 00:00:10.166
INTERVIEWER 1: Would you
like to live on the moon?

00:00:10.166 --> 00:00:11.100
WOMAN: Yes, I would.

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:12.433
INTERVIEWER 1: You would?

00:00:12.433 --> 00:00:13.700
You'd like to be one of
the first people to go?

00:00:13.700 --> 00:00:14.433
WOMAN: Yes.

00:00:21.333 --> 00:00:23.600
MAN 1: We have one of the most
challenging assignments that

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:28.200
has ever been given
to modern man.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:31.000
MAN 2: The United States'
man in space program

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.333
is at least eight months behind
that of the Soviet Union.

00:00:34.333 --> 00:00:37.600
Now it is time to take
longer strides, time

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:40.767
for this nation to
take a clearly leading

00:00:40.767 --> 00:00:44.200
role in space achievement.

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:45.533
MAN 3: It's there.

00:00:45.533 --> 00:00:47.867
We'd be neglecting our
duties as people if we

00:00:47.867 --> 00:00:51.000
didn't try to investigate it.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:53.934
ASTRONAUT 1: Oh, god, look
at that picture over there.

00:00:53.934 --> 00:00:55.700
There's the Earth coming up.

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:57.066
Wow, that's pretty.

00:00:57.066 --> 00:01:00.333
INTERVIEWER 2: You well may
be the first man on the moon.

00:01:00.333 --> 00:01:01.633
How do you personally
feel about it?

00:01:01.633 --> 00:01:03.166
ASTRONAUT 2: Well, I
have the same desires

00:01:03.166 --> 00:01:04.967
as all the astronauts.

00:01:04.967 --> 00:01:06.400
We'd all like to make that trip.

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.066
COUNTDOWN ANNOUNCER:
4, 3, 2, 1--

00:01:09.066 --> 00:01:09.934
[rockets firing]

00:01:09.934 --> 00:01:10.767
Liftoff.

00:01:10.767 --> 00:01:11.600
Roger, liftoff.

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:17.767
ANNOUNCER: [inaudible]
has cleared the tower,

00:01:17.767 --> 00:01:19.533
and there she goes, on
her way to the moon.

00:01:19.533 --> 00:01:21.567
GROUND CONTROLLER: Houston,
you are go for landing, over.

00:01:21.567 --> 00:01:22.667
[inaudible]

00:01:22.667 --> 00:01:23.900
NEWS ANNOUNCER: They
should be within five

00:01:23.900 --> 00:01:25.300
miles of their landing point.

00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:26.533
How's America looking, Bob?

00:01:26.533 --> 00:01:27.867
NEWS ANNOUNCER:
They're going in.

00:01:27.867 --> 00:01:30.200
ASTRONAUT 3: 2,000 feet,
picking up some dust.

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:32.100
Tranquility Base here.

00:01:32.100 --> 00:01:33.433
The Eagle has landed.

00:01:33.433 --> 00:01:34.834
GROUND CONTROLLER: We
copy you down, Eagle.

00:01:34.834 --> 00:01:37.700
[cheering]

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:43.166
[static]

00:01:43.166 --> 00:01:45.767
ASTRONAUT 4: Uh, Houston,
we've had a problem.

00:01:45.767 --> 00:01:47.233
ASTRONAUT 5: We got
more than a problem.

00:01:47.233 --> 00:01:48.400
GROUND CONTROLLER:
OK, stand by, 13.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:49.300
We're looking at it.

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:50.633
ASTRONAUT 5: [inaudible]

00:01:50.633 --> 00:01:52.567
MAN 3: It's a stepping
stone to deeper space.

00:01:52.567 --> 00:01:54.834
NEWS ANNOUNCER: It is no
longer a dream, but a reality.

00:01:54.834 --> 00:01:57.533
ASTRONAUT 6: Welcome
to the moon, Houston.

00:01:57.533 --> 00:02:01.200
GENE CERNAN: We leave as we
came, with peace and hope

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:03.400
for all mankind.

